I don&#39;t use UWP but i think the term you are describing here is Validation.  

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/wpf/advanced/dependency-property-callbacks-and-validation

It appears there is an overload of .Register() that takes validators.  You might do something like this

```
public static readonly DependencyProperty AgeProperty = DependencyProperty.Register(
    &quot;Age&quot;,
    typeof(int),
    typeof(Person),
    new FrameworkPropertyMetadata(
        0,
        callback
    ),
    new ValidateValueCallback(IsValidAge)
);


```

and then

```

public static bool IsValidAge(object value)
{
    int v = (int)value;
    return (v &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; v &lt; 150);
}

```

As you can see in the example, you can filter the data in Age&#39;s `Setter` and call the `SetValue()` method only if it meets the criteria.

```csharp
public int Age
{
    get { return (int)GetValue(AgeProperty); }
    set 
    {
        if (value &lt; 0)
        {
            // throw error or other things
        }
        else
        {
            SetValue(AgeProperty, value);
        }
    }
}
```

But if you want to adjust the controls that bind this property in XAML depending on the `Age`, you can consider using `IValueConverter`.

Here is the [document](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/uwp/api/windows.ui.xaml.data.ivalueconverter).

Best regards.

